metadata.name: Monsoon #32
metadata.description:
Optimization. It's something that haunts all programmers. Including me. But no longer! Monsoon is a study into the optimization of particle systems for the web. Looking especially deep into dynamic grids and dynamic frame rates.

As for the piece itself, it's a reference to how busy this modern world is. How we're all constantly on the go, whether that is physically, or mentally. Almost feeling like a monsoon. A storm of information. A storm of life. A storm of work. A storm of thoughts. A storm of emotions. A storm of everything. And it's all so fast.

As are the particles. They're all moving around these cyclones of information. Glowing up like neon signs in a busy city. Moving so fast it's almost a blur. Forming into something greater than the sum of its parts.

metadata.name: Schetsboek (reissue) #38
metadata.description:
This is my little tribute to fx (hash and fam).

During an important phone call, I was put on hold. Unconsciously, I began to scribble in my sketchbook. Research shows that scribbling helps focusing, but I dreamed away nonetheless until my pages were filled with scribbles, notes, shopping and a to-do list. 

Mint a uniquely generated page from my non-existent 100% coded sketchbook (except text typography). 

The page may contain many scribbles and drawings in pen, felt-tip pen, pencil, or less: often references to artists I admire, some in the form of loose scribbles, others in the form of riddles. Those drawings are drawn with code and vary. Unfortunately, I wasn‚Äôt able to incorporate tributes to all art and every artist I admire. The sketchbook would never finish. Thanks to rudxane I know that it‚Äôs ok to publish something unfinished ;-). 

One reference that appears in every token is to Sol Lewitt, an incredible source of inspiration. His artworks consist of instructions. Your sketch book pages contain instructions too. You will find the instructions for the artwork scribbled on your unique page by pressing i.

Curious how the work would look without the ‚Äòdistracting‚Äô scribbles and coffee stains? Press ‚Äòa‚Äô, ‚Äòw‚Äô, or ‚Äòg‚Äô. 

800 x 800 px

Press ‚Äòs‚Äô to save an image.

Made with p5js and the amazing p5.scribble.js library by Janneck Wullschleger.

Font used: Sacremento-Regular under the SIL Open Font License (OFL).

See license.md for the licenses of both.

Thank you all!

metadata.name: The Climb #77
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it‚Äôs about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

‚ÄúThe Climb‚Äù is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: Starmap - AI Study I #43
metadata.description:
Starmap brings you to different sectors of the generative art galaxy. A first of its kind generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow, which involves writing text prompts that get translated into javascript code. This project was created with English words and human imagination, but the programming of the piece is all AI.

The code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing some Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #1 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #86
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License

GPU intensive

metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #85
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js
